The Higgs Boson analyzes
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has caused a certain appearance last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle, whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "most false" explanation of nature and the behaviour of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it really is the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major Kyoto physics congress, but there is still no data to be completely secure about it.
Let's still assume that this is really the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let's look at what it is about.
There is a necessarily inevitable law in this world that causes two objects to not be present in the same place at the same time.
It's not possible to violate this rule - and don't try it too strong as you get hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantity state", with this "state" largely consisting of some of their characteristics.
From this point of view, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and likely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons, an evil band of anarchists who are not holy - certainly not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing) are divided into two groups: the mesons we are not being treated here and the "power particles" by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be stressed here that these bonons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bottom" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "distorted" at this location, in about a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of power".
Stable Field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "distorted" so that this boson shows itself.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen has to achieve very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could be shattered only by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a size of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, they are not all particles and not all materials interacting with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator by itself.
And likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do it have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these research now be "good", asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to investigate in detail all the deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
One has to say that the latter still has great defects, as it does not explain the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (renewed ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found in CERN.
Impact
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is no such thing.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who in 1962 himself developed the first continuous stroke laser (the first one was pulsated) - has already said that at the beginning the laser was considered a "laboratory".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in the optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and brought it the 2009 Nobel Prize for Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can never really know it...
Palliative care - the best way to die
Quebec has recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life with its "Deathing in Dignity" committee.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important subject area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer, which devoured him, had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I made seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the house for palliative care Victor Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The illness is doing its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to be able to help with the food.
He can even smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, since this is humiliating," he tells me.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our life, we learn that a man pees on the stand," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist in Victor-Gadbois's home.
Returning to childhood is unacceptable humiliation for certain persons.
"This depends on the person's ability", he says, taking a step backwards.
For, according to several people working in the palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these retreats.
The patients who are sent to the palliative care home Victor Gadbois, all suffer from cancer.
You have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, doctors and nurses who take care of them no longer have so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years, the worst fear of dying is "consciously and by suffocation".
But through the illness, I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more desires in life," she says before she accepts that she is put on a mask that helps her to breathe.
In the next few days, she is still expecting a last visit from her son, who is coming from Italy.
In the home Victor Gadbois, you can offer a group of volunteer body care and food intake assistance.
The palliative care is then used if there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 people.
That's very little if you take into account that one day we'll all die.
Here life will continue under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the physicians of the home.
Both on the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
A mouth care with Brandy or Pepsi is granted to the dying as desired.
Diabetics should no longer control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," reports Nathalie Savard.
In the home Victor Gadbois is not a day like the other.
In addition to an old 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, while invoking his honor, a 36-year-old young man dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife, and his two little children, tragically after trying to survive everything.
"For six months three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years of age," says Dr. Christiane Martel alarmedly.
53% of the patients assigned to Victor Gadbois's home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians have no access to palliative care, i.e. care to relieve the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their life, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as Victor Gadbois's home and the Society for Local Palliative Care in Montreal, are more or less specialized in caring for cancer patients.
Just this great inadequacy in Quebec's health care ensures that several doctors specializing in palliative care face the adoption of a law to regulate death aid and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe in order to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not capable enough to ensure that all the right to high-quality palliative care is guaranteed before you accept going to death aid.
Just a short time ago, she says, I saw a patient who had been in the emergency for 14 days without taking measures to relieve her.
I fear that the patients will only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
At the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of severe predictions until the last day.
The chances of survival of Hélène Richard were already minimal when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered to me that she was sorry I gave up the fight, she told me.
However, she told me that I was in the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the care staff that it has not allowed this wish after their pain has been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, Head of Palliative Care of the Society of Domestic Palliative Care of Greater Montreal, 8% of patients do not address pain treatment.
At the end of life, the doctors often resort to the terminal sedation that results in either sporadically or permanently inflicting the patient until the time of his death.
We can no longer do as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to access this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not eased all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be eased."
