It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "like the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits" used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes also exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, each time trade is controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of the invoice book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of related data are electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the accounts of the public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This happens via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner who is a kind of temporary central banker having the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a partitioning of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "cracked".
The aim is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
When this number is found, the other nodes can check effortlessly if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay with the same money twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) for fraud, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other will remain unplugged, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be shared up to a hundred millionths, leaving a certain amount of room...
In addition, the difficulty of the task will be increased with any improvement of the calculation performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for payment with real money and uses the network Bitcoin.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
