Are similar "large events" planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time in the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we will prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the USA already - would also like to associate this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already occurred in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group composed of people with disabilities.
How do you handle these travels logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it appears at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair drivers, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage room. Furthermore, we need to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems so far, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have already wondered in part.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad you have a comparison of what it looks like in each country with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than with us, we were just witnessing in Russia that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
Toward Prague, Moscow is absolutely not accessible to disabled people. There it is still unusual when someone is traveling in the wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even obvious that you leave a wheelchair driver in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, associations also arise there, trying to point to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways do we need to catch up with the developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're hanging back in...
However, it should also be noted that improvement of the situation is always dependent on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public space, go to the museum, use toilets etc.
But it is not common that a larger group of disabled people participate actively in social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when from our ranks important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly willful personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I began as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in working with something intensive.
