Poland and space.
Poland was admitted last week at a ministerial council meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency ESA as the twentieth member of this Space Authority. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland into space, of course, began much earlier.
Before World War II, Polish cosmosic enthusiasts were engaged in space, and they did not always come to terms with it.
For example, I recall the lecture by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entry to Cosmoautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934 for "Entry to the Cosmoautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important champion of astronomy and space.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to the development of space was honoured, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925 a railway-draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket-powered engine was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of the project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to brake the draisine.
The information for this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered shots.
The research was conducted by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents that have been handed down, it is clear that the research had been carried out to the stage of practical tests.
The research was, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket came up in the specialist press by Ing. Rohoziński, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliva-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects were concerned with the military use of rockets.
Shortly before the war, all the projects on the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work it was completed from the start of the war.
Further articles on space appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Poskie Towarzystwo Astronautczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society was made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the creation of a space company.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be seen that the exploration of space would have the future.
As early as 1956, the Polish Space Society PTA tried to join the International Federation of Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member in autumn 1956.
The following year the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), was appointed Chairman of the International Federation of Space.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been involved in the development of the highly successful meteorological missile (Raketa Meteorologicsna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and was not quite 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and 1959 began flight tests with the two-step RM-2 in the Błówdów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
He was the successor to RM's first rockets, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32,5 kg.
Three types (meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket has a transport room with 0.4 litres capacity, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C above 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height for all three types was 37 km.
In 1965 to 1968 the Meteor 2 rocket was developed in the aviation institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a load of 10 kg at a height of approximately 60 km.
The versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built afterwards.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COPPAR (Commission for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a national COPPAR Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites in the framework of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Republic of Vladimír Remek.
