Szabo: "Germans have to play a bigger role"
Germany has abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert in US-European relations, Berlin thus balances at a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for an observer status of the Palestinians to the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what Israelis did in Gaza.
Now Germany must be careful due to its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about setting up a flight ban zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to obtain a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is turning its foreign policy away from a policy, which was, so to speak, managed by the US, towards a German foreign policy.
Complicatedly, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans are thus opposed between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still touching their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, such as France or Great Britain.
What exactly does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to refer to national interests as well as positions independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
That is why it must be careful not to put an end to the public, but also to the elites, in the Arab countries.
That definitely plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to add too much weight to that either, that's not a totally one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German reflections.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by including itself in important decisions of the vote, for example in the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That's why I don't think this was such a dramatic break, as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even have a certain degree of respect for this.
Because it does signal that it is being taken seriously as international players and that its interests need to be considered.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly advocated a veto.
Are there differences between the US and many European nations?
These differences have always existed because of the American internal policy.
I believe that the government under Obama may secretly have quite a lot of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always appear.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so brightly enthusiastic about Netanjah's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the USA on the one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they can't be part of a wider line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, even because of the relationship with Israel.
That was always a sensitive theme.
But I believe that the Germans are clear that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany itself see itself in the role of important international players - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or does Germany still have difficulty taking the lead?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
If, for example, we look at the euro crisis, there are a wide range of anti-German feelings every time Germany takes a greater role.
It doesn't make the Germans easy.
That's actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Germany is thus in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be susceptible to various neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now, the influence of the US in European politics is constantly decreasing, but the EU is filling at the moment of this vacuum, who else remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
Even if they don't like it, they're uncomfortable and they make it much more unloving - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America are jointly investigating the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialises in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
