In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - to German for example: "The Incessant Mind: The Definition of Boring Under the Aspect of Attention" published in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others listened to low volume, so it was hardly noticeable, while the third group did not know these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they had more boredom than the two other groups - they had problems focusing on themselves, could not find any reason for this and wrote their difficulties of boredom.
If one tries to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neurosciences at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
