Completion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th summit of the Presidents of the Union of South America (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and should theoretically be signed by the seven rulers present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of the heads of state and government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidents' Office initially announced that they would hand it over after the clause, but subsequently explained that it would be published at some time on the website of the Peruvian government.
In the case of questions on the text, they stated that the content was presented to the press by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala.
Journalists' access to information on the summit was limited at any time.
During the day in the press room, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transferred with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among journalists was received by the press speakers of some of the Unasur’s governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press speaker.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which raised dissatisfaction among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the Presidential Office of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "Declaration" of the Summit, but it was the Declaration of Humala and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced before, was also not published in spite of a strong press call.
On the official website of the ASPA you can be convinced that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were available to journalists, but to a large extent they restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague, which contributes to a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which will begin on Monday in The Hague, in the trial that Lima launched against Santiago to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are currently presenting to this international court," said Humala together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, remains and remains a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and subjects itself to international courts," added Piñera and greeted Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the IGH was made after Colombia had, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a serious mistake to have filed an action against the Bogotá Convention, in which it agreed to subject itself to the judgments of this international court.
At the meeting, the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner were present.
Paraguay, who has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 following the resignation of his President Fernando Lugo, did not take part in the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks on the morning and ended the summit shortly after the noon in Lima.
The Head of State abandoned the final document, which reported that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment of $17 billion.
On the decisions taken, he said that the states of the Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, to which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He announced that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and against organised cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and to the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the case of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant traits, but rather should increase our production performance and show our people a better future", added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects to improve spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a read-only statement.
Among these projects would also include five Peruvians lying on the cross-axles of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which should ensure a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and for good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before his participation in the regional meeting that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to deal respectfully with the maritime conflict following a judgment of the IGH challenged by Bogotá.
"Maybe I'll meet President Daniel Ortega on tomorrow day (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and also the agreement with Nicaragua makes talks necessary with Nicaragua," he underlined.
"I hope to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilised and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present when taking over the new President Enrique Peña Nito.
As part of the summit, the Minister for Defence of the Block for the adoption of the 2013 Action Plan was also meeting in advance, with the aim of strengthening dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of the UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is presiding over the time of the regional block.
